plan is a
giveaway to the wealthy,
especially one big

10:05.138 --> 10:06.906 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
change.

10:06.940 --> 10:10.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON: In his
speech on Monday,
he called for a new tax loophole
-- let's

10:10.376 --> 10:18.251 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
call it the Trump loophole --
because it would
allow him to pay less than half
the current

10:18.284 --> 10:22.355 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tax rate on income from many of
his companies.

10:22.388 --> 10:26.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Clinton is
talking about
something complicated, but
important, called

10:26.226 --> 10:27.627 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
pass-through income.

10:27.660 --> 10:29.262 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Here's how it works.

10:29.295 --> 10:33.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Classically, a business pays a
35 percent
rate on taxable incomes.

10:33.800 --> 10:38.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But some businesses, where the
owner or family
is the business -- think about
attorneys with

10:38.438 --> 10:42.809 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
their own firms, for example --
can pay using
what's called a pass-through.

10:42.842 --> 10:46.779 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In that case, the business
doesn't pay a corporate
tax.

10:46.813 --> 10:51.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Instead, the company pays the
owner and the
owner pays an individual income
tax of up

10:51.584 --> 10:54.587 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to 39.6 percent.

10:54.621 --> 10:59.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This exists so the owner isn't
taxed twice,
as a business and individual.

10:59.692 --> 11:04.197 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Donald Trump's plan would cut
all corporate
taxes to 15 percent.

11:04.230 --> 11:10.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he would set a new 15
percent rate for
these pass-through incomes, a
huge cut that

11:10.470 --> 11:13.072 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
could apply to his own
businesses.

11:13.106 --> 11:16.776 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He responds that Clinton and
Democrats overtax
companies.

11:16.809 --> 11:23.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: All Hillary
Clinton has to offer
is more of the same, more taxes,
more regulations,

11:23.216 --> 11:28.988 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
more bureaucrats, more
restrictions on American
energy and on American
production.

11:29.022 --> 11:34.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Different
visions, Trump
offering tax cuts to all,
especially the wealthy,

11:34.594 --> 11:39.065 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Clinton pledging to tax the
wealthy more and
to use that money for programs
for the middle

11:39.098 --> 11:42.869 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and lower classes, including
targeted tax
credits.

11:42.902 --> 11:45.305 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Lisa
Desjardins.

11:45.338 --> 11:51.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Clearly, there
are still many
other details to both of their
plans, but

11:51.110 --> 11:56.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
let's focus in on some of the
bigger differences
of their approaches to taxes
with Neil Irwin.

11:56.616 --> 12:00.853 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He reports on business and
economic issues
for The New York Times.

12:00.887 --> 12:05.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And David Wessel, director of
the Hutchins
Center on Fiscal and Monetary
Policy at the

12:05.992 --> 12:11.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Brookings Institution, and a
contributing
correspondent for The Wall
Street Journal.

12:11.264 --> 12:13.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we welcome both of you back
to the program.

12:13.499 --> 12:16.603 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think both of you agree
with what we
have just been hearing.

12:16.636 --> 12:21.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The biggest differences between
Clinton and
Trump are over how their tax
plans treat the

12:21.608 --> 12:22.575 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
wealthy.

12:22.609 --> 12:24.544 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
David, spell that out a little
more for us.

12:24.577 --> 12:26.279 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What's the difference?

12:26.312 --> 12:28.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID WESSEL, The Wall Street
Journal: Well,
Hillary Clinton has a very clear
strategy

12:28.081 --> 12:30.717 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of increasing taxes on the
wealthy.

12:30.750 --> 12:33.019 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She would increase the estate
tax.

12:33.052 --> 12:37.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She would increase, as Lisa's
piece said,
the marginal income tax rate on
the highest

12:37.390 --> 12:39.425 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
income earners.

12:39.459 --> 12:44.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trump, on the other hand, would
lower taxes
for pretty much everybody, but
he would disproportionately

12:44.330 --> 12:46.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
lower them for people at the
top.

12:46.499 --> 12:48.568 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he would do away with the
estate tax.

12:48.601 --> 12:54.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, in a sense, she wants to use
the tax code
to narrow the gap between
winners and losers

12:54.440 --> 12:57.977 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in our economy, and he doesn't
make that a
priority.

12:58.011 --> 13:03.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He wants to lower taxes and says
that that
will somehow unleash a burst of
economy growth.

13:03.182 --> 13:07.687 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Neil, remind
us, how do
we define wealthy here?

13:07.720 --> 13:09.722 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What income levels are we
talking about?

13:09.756 --> 13:12.291 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NEIL IRWIN, The New York Times:
Well, with
Hillary Clinton, the biggest
surcharge is

13:12.325 --> 13:14.761 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for people making over $5
million a year.

13:14.794 --> 13:16.629 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's the very, very wealthy.

13:16.663 --> 13:20.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But she has some other
provisions that affect
people a little further down the
income scale,

13:20.833 --> 13:24.804 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some provisions that make sure
people making
over $1 million pay at least 30
percent.

13:24.837 --> 13:28.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That includes -- so that deals
with the issue
that Warren Buffett has talked
about where

13:28.741 --> 13:32.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some secretaries, middle-class
people can
end up with effectively a higher
rate than

13:32.445 --> 13:34.447 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people who make their income
through capital
gains.

13:34.480 --> 13:38.785 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it's kind of a multitiered
effort she's
doing to use some different
dials within the

13:38.818 --> 13:42.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tax code to try and shift
overall the burden
a little heavier toward the
affluent.

13:42.655 --> 13:47.860 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now, in
connection with that,
David, let's talk about what the
two of them

13:47.894 --> 13:50.596 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
would do when it comes to
corporations and
businesses.

13:50.630 --> 13:54.434 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I know there's a lot here,
you know, we
could focus on.

13:54.467 --> 13:57.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, mainly, what are the
differences between
the two?

13:57.203 --> 14:02.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID WESSEL: Well, the main
difference is
that Donald Trump wants to cut
the tax on

14:02.241 --> 14:04.911 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
businesses, and she doesn't.

14:04.944 --> 14:06.646 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's pretty simple like that.

14:06.679 --> 14:11.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She has a number of targeted tax
breaks for
businesses to encourage them to
do things

14:11.517 --> 14:15.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that she and her advisers think
would be good
for the economy, more
apprenticeships, more

14:15.855 --> 14:17.757 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
profit-sharing.

14:17.790 --> 14:22.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But he is willing to cut the
rate, allow them
to write off a lot more stuff
more quickly.

14:22.995 --> 14:27.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, one advantage he has, he
doesn't pay
for any of this stuff.

14:27.066 --> 14:30.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So she's very carefully, you
increase this,
you cut that.

14:30.603 --> 14:34.307 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's not making the long-term
deficit better,
but she's not making it worse.

14:34.340 --> 14:37.243 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He seems unconcerned with that,
so he can
give a lot more tax breaks.

14:37.276 --> 14:40.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, revenue
overall to the
Treasury, to the government
would go down

14:40.646 --> 14:41.681 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
under his proposal?

14:41.714 --> 14:43.416 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID WESSEL: A lot, yes,
trillions of dollars.

14:43.449 --> 14:48.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Neil, be a little
bit more
specific on that, Neil, because
we have talked

14:48.221 --> 14:52.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about -- Lisa referred to
something called
the pass-through, where if
somebody owns a

14:52.658 --> 14:58.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
business, they -- again, without
confusing
everybody, what does that
really, effectively

14:58.097 --> 14:59.031 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
mean?

14:59.065 --> 15:01.601 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NEIL IRWIN: It's kind of a big
deal.

15:01.634 --> 15:05.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Donald Trump talks about doing a
15 percent
rate on business income, not
just corporations

15:05.571 --> 15:12.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
like Apple or GE, but also on
small businesses,
including partnerships,
including if I have

15:12.478 --> 15:17.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a sole proprietorship, if I have
a small partnership,
he wants a 15 percent rate on
that income

15:17.450 --> 15:22.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as well, which means it creates
great incentive
-- if you're a wealthy person
looking at a

15:22.488 --> 15:27.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
40 percent rate in the current
tax code, 33
percent under Trump's plan, you
can actually

15:27.160 --> 15:31.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
get that down to 15 percent if
you can somehow
route that income through a
business, through

15:31.430 --> 15:32.899 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a partnership.

15:32.932 --> 15:34.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what we will see if that
happens is a
lot of people trying to do that.

15:34.734 --> 15:36.669 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID WESSEL: Right.

15:36.702 --> 15:39.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So what's interesting is if
you're a wage-earner,
if you get a paycheck from your
boss, there's

15:39.939 --> 15:42.942 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
no way you're going to be able
to take advantage
of this.

15:42.975 --> 15:47.947 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if you can somehow turn
yourself into
a little company, a lawyer who
is a partner,

15:47.980 --> 15:54.287 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
or you're some kind of a
baseball player who
says, I'm now I'm -- I'm David
Wessel, Incorporated,

15:54.320 --> 15:56.989 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
then I can take advantage of
this.

15:57.023 --> 16:01.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So a whole set of people, if
they can organize
themselves as businesses, can
take advantage

16:02.028 --> 16:02.995 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of this.

16:03.029 --> 16:04.330 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Ordinary wage-earners can't.

16:04.363 --> 16:05.665 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And is it
expected that that
would happen, Neil?

16:05.698 --> 16:07.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NEIL IRWIN: It is.

16:07.166 --> 16:09.101 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The government -- the law can
try and do things
to try and fight it.

16:09.135 --> 16:12.305 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we already see some of this
that happens
to avoid payroll taxes.

16:12.338 --> 16:14.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is clearly one of the issues
that will
have to be resolved.

16:14.841 --> 16:18.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: In connection
with this, we
often hear Donald Trump talk
about corporate

16:18.477 --> 16:20.546 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tax rates are way too high in
this country.

16:20.580 --> 16:26.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The effective rate, though,
David, as I understand
it, is lower than what the
number is.

16:26.452 --> 16:30.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
People end up paying less, or
companies end
up paying less than what they
are charged

16:30.990 --> 16:31.958 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on paper.

16:31.991 --> 16:33.693 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID WESSEL: Right.

16:33.726 --> 16:36.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the statutory rate, the rate
in the law
is 35 percent, but when you look
at all the

16:36.562 --> 16:41.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
deductions and credits and
exclusions that
we give businesses, the
effective rate, on

16:41.200 --> 16:43.669 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
average, is much lower than
that, in the 20s.

16:43.703 --> 16:45.304 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
For some companies, it's higher.

16:45.338 --> 16:47.106 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Some companies, it is lower.

16:47.139 --> 16:51.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, there is a lot of momentum
in Washington
to redo the corporate tax code,
take away

16:51.811 --> 16:54.714 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some of these deductions and
credits, and
lower the rates.

16:54.747 --> 16:58.050 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's been very politically
difficult because
there are winners and losers.

16:58.084 --> 17:01.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And actually neither candidate
has gotten
very specific about how they do
that.

17:01.587 --> 17:04.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, I want to
ask you both
about the middle class, people
earning less

17:04.457 --> 17:05.758 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
than what the wealthy do.

17:05.791 --> 17:09.095 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But before we do, Neil, what
about changes
in the estate tax?

17:09.128 --> 17:12.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is the tax people are
charged when they
die.

17:12.298 --> 17:16.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They pass on everything they
have to their
children and there's a tax
associated with

17:16.035 --> 17:17.003 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that.

17:17.036 --> 17:18.004 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How do Clinton and Trump deal
with that?

17:18.037 --> 17:19.038 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NEIL IRWIN: Well, with Trump,
it's simple.

17:19.071 --> 17:20.773 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He wants to get rid of it
entirely.

17:20.806 --> 17:24.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one thing to remember, right
now, the
cutoff there for a married
couple, it's $10.9

17:24.911 --> 17:30.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
million, meaning you have to be
a multimillionaire
when a person dies to face that
tax at all.

17:30.449 --> 17:32.218 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He still wants to get rid of it.

17:32.251 --> 17:36.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hillary Clinton wants to go the
other direction,
reduce those exemptions down to
$7 million

17:36.856 --> 17:38.491 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for a married couple.

17:38.524 --> 17:40.860 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it would affect more people
than it does
now if Hillary Clinton got her
way.

17:40.893 --> 17:43.462 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, again, what
would the
effect be on revenue, David?

17:43.496 --> 17:46.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID WESSEL: Well, we don't get
a lot of
revenue from the estate tax.

17:46.699 --> 17:47.967 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We know the direction.

17:48.000 --> 17:49.802 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I think what Neil says is
really important.

17:49.835 --> 17:56.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, of every 1,000 people who
die in a given
year, only two of them face the
estate tax.

17:56.475 --> 17:59.412 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, it affects only the very
rich.

17:59.445 --> 18:02.415 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's almost more of a talking
point than it
is a real tax policy.

18:02.448 --> 18:05.084 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We often hear
Republicans refer
to it as the death tax.

18:05.117 --> 18:06.085 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID WESSEL: Right.

18:06.118 --> 18:07.086 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right.

18:07.119 --> 18:08.087 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I don't why they do that.

18:08.120 --> 18:09.822 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

18:09.855 --> 18:14.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Let's talk about,
Neil, the
middle class, and let's be clear
about what

18:14.393 --> 18:18.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bracket, what income bracket
we're talking
about, because, again, we see
differences

18:18.664 --> 18:21.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
between the two of them and what
they would
do with the tax rates.

18:21.200 --> 18:22.268 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
NEIL IRWIN: Yes.

18:22.301 --> 18:24.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, Donald Trump does have a
middle-class
tax cut.

18:24.203 --> 18:25.538 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's fairly small.

18:25.571 --> 18:30.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's moving one of the key
brackets from 15
percent to 12 percent.

18:30.276 --> 18:33.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One estimate, the proposal his
is based on
would cut after tax income for
middle-class

18:34.013 --> 18:38.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
families by something like 0.2
percent, something
like 5 percent for the richest 1
percent.

18:38.918 --> 18:41.120 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, he does have that tax cut in
there.

18:41.153 --> 18:42.922 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Hillary doesn't.

18:42.955 --> 18:45.124 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The question, though, is, is the
scale that
they're talking about something
that is going

18:45.157 --> 18:48.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to really move the dial and
change living
standards for middle-class
Americans?

18:48.427 --> 18:50.196 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the numbers just aren't that
big.

18:50.229 --> 18:52.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we should
say, David, that
Trump has been saying the last
several days

18:52.865 --> 18:55.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that Clinton favors raising
taxes on the middle
class.

18:55.935 --> 18:57.370 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She says absolutely she does
not.

18:57.403 --> 18:59.238 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID WESSEL: Right.

18:59.271 --> 19:01.941 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In her -- in the proposals she
has laid out,
she doesn't raise taxes on the
middle class.

19:01.974 --> 19:06.979 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, how do you
single out the
differences there on what
happens to the middle

19:07.013 --> 19:08.848 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
class?

19:08.881 --> 19:11.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID WESSEL: Well, as I said,
because Trump
is cutting taxes for a lot of
people and not

19:11.117 --> 19:16.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
paying for it, he's able to
offer some tax
cuts, like the one Neil
described.

19:16.255 --> 19:23.295 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Hillary Clinton has some
targeted tax cuts,
like increasing the tax break
for child care,

19:23.329 --> 19:27.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which she has now responded to
in a vague
and evolving way.

19:27.500 --> 19:31.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, when you step back,
what Hillary
Clinton is really saying is,
look, some people

19:31.070 --> 19:33.806 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are going to have to pay more
taxes.

19:33.839 --> 19:38.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm going to come up with a plan
that puts
all those tax increases on
people who make

19:38.477 --> 19:41.013 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
more than $250,000 a year.

19:41.047 --> 19:44.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm not going to be able to do
very much for
people who make less than that.

19:44.450 --> 19:47.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm not going to cut their taxes
much, but
I'm also not going to raise
them.

19:47.686 --> 19:49.488 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What would you to
do that,
Neil?

19:49.522 --> 19:53.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we should say that whatever
candidates
say during a campaign is not
always necessarily

19:53.125 --> 19:55.227 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what they can get passed once
they're elected.

19:55.261 --> 19:56.262 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NEIL IRWIN: That's always true.

19:56.295 --> 19:59.298 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There is also some stuff on
child tax credits.

19:59.331 --> 20:03.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hillary Clinton talks about it
as a credit
that would help a lot of
middle-class, lower-income

20:03.102 --> 20:05.871 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
families afford child care.

20:05.905 --> 20:07.606 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Donald Trump wants to do it as a
deduction.

20:07.640 --> 20:11.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That would mainly apply to the
wealthiest
Americans, upper-middle-class
families.

20:11.610 --> 20:13.345 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, that's another key
distinction in this.

20:13.379 --> 20:16.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID WESSEL: We should mention
that they
both talk about college and
student loans

20:16.816 --> 20:18.417 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in different forms.

20:18.451 --> 20:21.187 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Hillary is talking about making
college debt-free.

20:21.220 --> 20:24.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so that would obviously be
things that
are targeted to the middle
class.

20:24.423 --> 20:27.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think Hillary Clinton is
also saying,
look, I want to spend a lot of
money on pre-K

20:27.960 --> 20:31.664 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and infrastructure, and that
will help people
get jobs and higher wages.

20:31.697 --> 20:34.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, there is a
whole lot
to look at with their economic
plans.

20:34.600 --> 20:35.901 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This has taken a big bite out of
it.

20:35.935 --> 20:42.041 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we thank you both, Neil
Irwin, David Wessel.

20:42.074 --> 20:48.714 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID WESSEL: You're welcome.

20:48.747 --> 20:55.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: As the summer's
political and
foreign policy debate has
focused overwhelmingly

20:55.721 --> 21:01.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on the rise of ISIS, an old foe
continues
to threaten lives and security
in Afghanistan.

21:01.727 --> 21:06.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Taliban have been closing in
on Lashkar
Gah, the capital of Helmand
Province, forcing

21:06.832 --> 21:10.970 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
residents to flee as the Afghan
army struggles
to contain them.

21:11.003 --> 21:15.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more on this, I'm joined now
from Kabul
by special correspondent
Jennifer Glasse.

21:15.107 --> 21:16.342 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Jennifer, welcome.

21:16.375 --> 21:19.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have been to Lashkar Gah, to
the provincial
capital.

21:19.078 --> 21:21.814 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tell us, what is important about
that and
what is happening there?

21:21.847 --> 21:24.250 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: Well, the
people down there
are very concerned.

21:24.283 --> 21:29.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Taliban in the last week or
so have basically
encircled the city, taken many
of the road

21:29.789 --> 21:31.557 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
leading into and out of the
town.

21:31.590 --> 21:36.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They say they feel besieged;
30,000 people
have been displaced just in the
last couple

21:36.095 --> 21:41.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of weeks alone, and the Afghan
army is struggling
to contain the Taliban and to
keep them out

21:41.167 --> 21:43.035 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of the provincial capital.

21:43.068 --> 21:46.238 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, if the Taliban were to
assault provincial
capital, it would be the first
time they have

21:46.272 --> 21:48.140 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
tried it since 2008.

21:48.174 --> 21:49.708 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That assault was beaten back.

21:49.742 --> 21:52.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, of course, it's been a
difficult time
for them.

21:52.378 --> 21:54.313 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They have some help down there.

21:54.346 --> 21:56.515 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Afghan forces have sent down
reinforcements.

21:56.549 --> 21:58.717 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have help in the form of
American airstrikes.

21:58.751 --> 22:04.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
U.S. officials say there have
been at least
25 U.S. airstrikes in the past
two weeks alone

22:04.123 --> 22:06.892 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as the Taliban have mounted that
offensive.

22:06.926 --> 22:10.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Probably the biggest problem is
that they
are controlling many of the
routes in and

22:10.429 --> 22:16.835 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out of the city, including the
main road between
Lashkar Gah and Kandahar, the
two big cities

22:16.869 --> 22:18.871 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in Southern Afghanistan.

22:18.904 --> 22:22.441 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This -- of course, Helmand has
always been
a contested province.

22:22.474 --> 22:25.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The fighting down there has been
particularly
fierce.

22:25.377 --> 22:29.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
More than 125 U.S. soldiers have
lost their
lives there, including one
soldier who died

22:29.915 --> 22:32.751 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in January in fighting in
Helmand Province.

22:32.785 --> 22:38.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
About 400 British soldiers, as
well as another
100 or so coalition forces have
died during

22:38.357 --> 22:40.092 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the conflict in Helmand
Province.

22:40.125 --> 22:43.095 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it has always been a heavily
contested
province, but the fact that the
Taliban are

22:43.128 --> 22:48.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
making an offensive, making
advances on the
provincial capital, I think,
shows that they

22:48.200 --> 22:49.969 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are resurgent here, Gwen.

22:50.002 --> 22:53.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: What effect have
those -- you
talked about the U.S.
airstrikes, the 25 U.S.

22:53.939 --> 22:54.907 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
airstrikes.

22:54.940 --> 22:56.742 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What visible effect have they
had?

22:56.775 --> 23:01.280 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JENNIFER GLASSE: Well,
certainly, they have
helped move the Taliban back or
keep the Taliban

23:01.313 --> 23:06.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from forming in big groups,
because that's
what we have seen since the
drawdown of U.S.

23:06.085 --> 23:10.556 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
forces, since the withdrawal of
NATO forces,
the end of 2014.

23:10.589 --> 23:14.360 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Without that airpower, the
Taliban were able
to group in large numbers.

23:14.393 --> 23:16.128 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's what the airstrikes
are helping.

23:16.161 --> 23:22.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, U.S. officials also say
there are combat
enablers on the ground in
Lashkar Gah, in

23:22.735 --> 23:24.236 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Helmand Province.

23:24.270 --> 23:27.172 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, that could mean forces on
the ground,
fighting forces on the ground.

23:27.206 --> 23:31.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That could also mean spotters
who help target
those airstrikes more
effectively.

23:31.977 --> 23:37.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are also several hundred
American advisers
that went down there last year
to help reform

23:37.449 --> 23:42.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the 215 Army Corps that is in
Lashkar Gah,
that is in Helmand Province,
trying to hold

23:42.421 --> 23:46.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that province together, helping
with, main
role, training, advising and
assisting the

23:46.358 --> 23:47.326 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Afghan forces.

23:47.359 --> 23:49.261 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But the Afghan force is clearly
struggling.

23:49.295 --> 23:54.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Why are the Afghan
forces, why
do they appear to be so weak,
after all of

23:54.433 --> 23:59.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the support they have gotten,
not only from
the U.S., but also in training
and advising?

24:00.005 --> 24:01.440 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What has gone wrong, if
anything?

24:01.473 --> 24:04.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: Well, there are
a number
of problems.

24:04.376 --> 24:05.744 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
A lot of it is inexperience.

24:05.778 --> 24:08.147 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It is still a relatively new
force.

24:08.180 --> 24:12.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
U.S. officials say they are
better this year
than they were last year because
they have

24:12.084 --> 24:13.485 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
some combat experience.

24:13.519 --> 24:16.155 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have a little bit of better
strategic
experience.

24:16.188 --> 24:20.326 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there have been American
advisers down
there helping with the force.

24:20.359 --> 24:21.860 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Problems with leadership.

24:21.894 --> 24:27.399 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Many of the generals and
officials down there
have been changed or moved out.

24:27.433 --> 24:29.234 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Problems with strategy.

24:29.268 --> 24:32.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, one of the things that the
Afghans used
to do was go and set up
checkpoints on roads.

24:32.571 --> 24:35.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They, of course, were easy
targets for the
Taliban.

24:35.507 --> 24:41.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What the U.S. forces and other
NATO advisers
are trying to help them with is
to actually

24:41.113 --> 24:45.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
go and take land that they need
to take, hold
land that they need to hold.

24:45.451 --> 24:49.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it's definitely been a
struggle in the
last week or so around Lashkar
Gah, as the

24:49.855 --> 24:53.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Taliban have made a concerted
offensive there,
in some cases even blowing up
bridges.

24:53.959 --> 24:57.763 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the Afghan security forces
-- also with
a fledgling air force.

24:57.796 --> 24:59.264 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, they don't have their own
airpower.

24:59.298 --> 25:01.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's why the U.S. has
introduced its
airpower.

25:01.667 --> 25:03.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And the Taliban, how
strong is
it?

25:04.002 --> 25:07.740 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We went through this back and
forth in Kunduz
not long ago.

25:07.773 --> 25:13.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: Well, it's not
really whether
at this point Lashkar Gah falls
or not.

25:13.112 --> 25:15.414 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It really is the psychological
battle.

25:15.447 --> 25:21.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, last week, the Taliban went
into a district
south of Lashkar Gah, in the
Helmand River,

25:21.353 --> 25:23.889 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
went into the district center
for a brief
point of time.

25:23.922 --> 25:26.191 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then the enemy army pushed
them back.

25:26.225 --> 25:29.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's really not whether they can
hold the
area, because in Kunduz in the
north, they

25:29.795 --> 25:32.598 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
only held the city center for
about three
days.

25:32.631 --> 25:37.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the knock-on effect of that
was really
very dramatic, because it
instilled fear in

25:37.536 --> 25:38.504 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
people.

25:38.537 --> 25:39.505 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They did go around.

25:39.538 --> 25:40.672 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They gathered a lot of
intelligence.

25:40.706 --> 25:42.875 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They gathered people's names in
Kunduz.

25:42.908 --> 25:45.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the concern, of course, of
the people
in Lashkar Gah, if they are able
to get into

25:45.978 --> 25:49.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the city, are able to get close
as they have
gotten, it just shows that they
still are

25:50.015 --> 25:51.683 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a resurgent Taliban.

25:51.717 --> 25:54.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And people are very concerned,
not just in
Helmand Province, but around the
country,

25:54.953 --> 25:57.456 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that the Taliban have been able
to make such
gains.

25:57.489 --> 26:02.261 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Jennifer Glasse
reporting for
us tonight from Kabul, thank you
so much.

26:02.294 --> 26:12.137 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: Good to talk to
you, Gwen.

26:12.171 --> 26:15.407 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

26:15.441 --> 26:19.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": how
New York
City's High Line changed the way
we think

26:19.711 --> 26:26.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about parks; virus hunters
tasked with tracking
down the next outbreak before it
happens;

26:26.885 --> 26:30.389 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and a filmmaker and poet making
her Olympic
debut.

26:30.422 --> 26:35.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, first: One question looming
over this
election is, what is the best
way to boost

26:35.727 --> 26:37.563 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the economy?

26:37.596 --> 26:42.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This week, the government
reported worker
productivity, which can affect
wages and growth,

26:42.534 --> 26:47.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
