quarter, the
longest slide since the late
'70s.

26:47.372 --> 26:51.543 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some economists are asking if
slower growth
is the new normal.

26:51.577 --> 26:54.713 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Economics correspondent Paul
Solman has been
exploring that question.

26:54.746 --> 26:56.381 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Here's a second look.

26:56.415 --> 27:00.452 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's part of our series on
Making Sense of
financial news, which airs
Thursday.

27:00.486 --> 27:05.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: President Obama's
last of State
of the Union featured this proud
proclamation:

27:05.157 --> 27:09.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States:
Anyone claiming that America's
economy is

27:09.394 --> 27:11.697 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in decline is peddling fiction.

27:11.730 --> 27:13.665 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: But really?

27:13.699 --> 27:19.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tell that to eminent economist
Robert Gordon,
a Democrat, who's peddling a
distinctly nonfictional

27:19.838 --> 27:23.442 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
new book, "The Rise and Fall of
American Growth."

27:23.475 --> 27:25.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON, Author, "The Rise
and Fall
of American Growth": Did you
know that the

27:25.677 --> 27:31.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cable car dates back to 1870,
the beginning
of what I call the special
century, when life

27:31.183 --> 27:34.186 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
was revolutionized in the United
States?

27:34.219 --> 27:40.692 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: A century that
ended in 1970,
46 years ago.

27:40.726 --> 27:45.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Gordon's thesis that slower
growth is the
new normal in the U.S. has
sparked a major

27:45.097 --> 27:48.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
debate in economics the past few
years.

27:48.267 --> 27:53.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
His book was a hot topic at this
year's meeting
of the American Economic
Association in San

27:53.705 --> 27:55.040 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Francisco.

27:55.073 --> 27:57.042 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BOB SHILLER, Nobel Laureate:
It's what you
call a magnum opus.

27:57.075 --> 28:01.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: That's Nobel
laureate Bob Shiller,
this year's president of the
group, who organized

28:01.547 --> 28:08.787 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a session on the new book and
chaired it himself
to spotlight Gordon and his
special century

28:08.820 --> 28:10.589 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
thesis.

28:10.622 --> 28:14.526 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON: A century that
freed households
from an unremitting daily grind
of gainful

28:14.560 --> 28:19.798 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
manual labor, household
drudgery, darkness,
isolation and early death.

28:19.831 --> 28:25.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: There seems little
dispute in
economics these days that 1870
to 1970 was

28:25.437 --> 28:27.105 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
technologically special.

28:27.139 --> 28:31.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN: No one who hasn't cooked
over a wood
stove by the light of a kerosene
lamp can

28:31.577 --> 28:33.178 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
really appreciate what it all
means.

28:33.211 --> 28:35.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So it was an
amazing century,
right?

28:35.213 --> 28:37.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ERIK BRYNJOLFSSON, Massachusetts
Institute
of Technology: It was an amazing
century.

28:37.249 --> 28:41.553 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We took so much muscle power,
things that
used to be done by horses or by
humans, and

28:41.587 --> 28:43.488 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
replaced it with machines.

28:43.522 --> 28:47.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But MIT's Erik
Brynjolfsson doesn't
buy the argument that the U.S.
economy's best

28:47.793 --> 28:49.528 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
days are over.

28:49.561 --> 28:51.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ERIK BRYNJOLFSSON: We're now
just in the early
stages of what we sometimes call
a second

28:51.530 --> 28:56.969 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
machine age, where we're
beginning to do the
same things for brainpower,
things like artificial

28:57.002 --> 28:59.605 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
intelligence, computers and big
data.

28:59.638 --> 29:02.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think we're going to see a
productivity
wave the likes of which we have
never seen

29:03.008 --> 29:04.710 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
before.

29:04.743 --> 29:08.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON: It's just a hope
that Erik
has that these new inventions of
robots and

29:08.780 --> 29:13.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
artificial intelligence are
going to change
the world on a par with
electricity and the

29:13.952 --> 29:15.587 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
internal combustion engine.

29:15.621 --> 29:18.757 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Just think of the benefits of
getting rid
of the urban horse.

29:18.790 --> 29:22.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Think of all the horse droppings
all over
the street that we no longer
have to think

29:22.327 --> 29:24.062 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
about and clean up.

29:24.096 --> 29:27.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: To counter those
who consider
his cavalier dismissal of high
technology

29:27.432 --> 29:32.738 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so much, well, horse manure,
Gordon took us
on an intimate show-and-tell.

29:32.771 --> 29:35.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON: Look at a few of
the things
that were invented in the
special century

29:35.841 --> 29:40.545 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
after 1870, starting with the
electric light,
the greatest invention of all.

29:40.579 --> 29:44.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And now let's look at two of the
great inventions
of all time.

29:44.316 --> 29:49.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First, we have running water,
which eliminated
the need to carry water into the
house in

29:49.154 --> 29:51.023 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
pails.

29:51.056 --> 29:55.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then we have the flush
toilet, which eliminated
the need to go outside into the
bitter cold

29:55.827 --> 29:57.362 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to an outhouse.

29:57.396 --> 30:02.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And here we have a double
invention, central
heating and air conditioning.

30:02.134 --> 30:05.337 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have the telephone invented
in 1876.

30:05.370 --> 30:10.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have the television set,
partly invented
here in San Francisco by
Philosophy Farnsworth,

30:10.342 --> 30:15.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and then look what we have
hidden down here,
a refrigerator, which eliminated
the contamination

30:15.847 --> 30:17.783 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of food.

30:17.816 --> 30:21.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And here we have the Golden Gate
Bridge, an
example of the tremendous
investment in infrastructure

30:21.720 --> 30:25.457 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that made our economy grow so
fast in the
middle of the 20th century.

30:25.490 --> 30:27.492 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This bridge was finished in
1937.

30:27.526 --> 30:30.262 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NARRATOR: The Golden Gate is
bridged.

30:30.295 --> 30:36.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Put them all
together, says Gordon,
and there's been no comparable
stretch of

30:36.101 --> 30:39.738 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
economic growth before or since.

30:39.771 --> 30:43.975 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON: Here is the basic
point of
my book.

30:44.009 --> 30:49.314 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The early 20th century, the
middle of the
20th century between 1920 and
1970, and all

30:49.347 --> 30:55.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the years since then, and the
role of innovation
and technology is that black
area at the bottom.

30:55.187 --> 30:59.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when we highlight it we see
that in the
middle of the 20th century, we
were growing

30:59.357 --> 31:02.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
three times faster than we have
been in the
last 40 years.

31:02.961 --> 31:09.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And not only were
the really
big inventions already on the
market by 1970.

31:09.301 --> 31:15.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This footage of the 1962 Seattle
World's Fair
suggests the ones we consider
big today were

31:15.941 --> 31:17.709 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
already in the works.

31:17.743 --> 31:22.214 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NARRATOR: One day, you may be
able to call
home and automatically turn off
the oven or,

31:22.247 --> 31:27.586 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from a public telephone, water
the lawn during
that dry spell when you are many
miles away

31:27.619 --> 31:28.587 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on vacation.

31:28.620 --> 31:30.155 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Sounds fantastic, doesn't it?

31:30.188 --> 31:33.759 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Critics like
Brynjolfsson don't
dispute the wonders of the past.

31:33.792 --> 31:36.094 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They just think we haven't seen
anything yet.

31:36.128 --> 31:39.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ERIK BRYNJOLFSSON: It's been
said that the
greatest failing of the human
mind is the

31:39.464 --> 31:41.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
inability to understand the
exponential function.

31:41.533 --> 31:46.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's especially true in
the computer
era, where computer power
doubles about every

31:46.204 --> 31:47.806 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
24 months or so.

31:47.839 --> 31:51.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Exponential growth
like 2-4-8-16
and so on.

31:51.476 --> 31:55.447 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ERIK BRYNJOLFSSON: What that
does is, it leads
us to overestimate what's going
to happen

31:55.480 --> 31:59.017 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the short run, because at
first it's happening
fairly slowly, but then we
underestimate what

31:59.050 --> 32:00.952 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
happens in the long run, when
things really
take off.

32:00.986 --> 32:02.788 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Bob Gordon scoffs.

32:02.821 --> 32:06.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON: But computers
have been riding
this exponential wave for the
last 50 years,

32:06.758 --> 32:08.226 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and it's not shown up in
productivity.

32:08.260 --> 32:12.130 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: In measured GDP
output per unit
of labor, that is.

32:12.164 --> 32:16.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON: We have gone from
the mainframe
to the personal computer to the
smartphone,

32:16.468 --> 32:23.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and only in the late 1990s did
we see a revival
of productivity growth of the
kind of magnitude

32:23.175 --> 32:27.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to match the great old days of
electricity
and the invention of the
motorcar and the

32:27.779 --> 32:29.581 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
airplane.

32:29.614 --> 32:33.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Productivity, says
Gordon, has
slowed to a crawl for years now,
what's called

32:33.952 --> 32:36.254 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
long-term or secular stagnation.

32:36.288 --> 32:39.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ERIK BRYNJOLFSSON: The last time
people were
talking a lot about stagnation
was in the

32:39.991 --> 32:41.126 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
1930s.

32:41.159 --> 32:42.627 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And guess what?

32:42.661 --> 32:46.398 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The next couple of decades were
the best decades
ever for economic growth.

32:46.431 --> 32:51.236 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Admittedly,
Americans have been
techno-overoptimists before.

32:51.269 --> 32:56.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ACTOR: The 9000 series is the
most reliable
computer ever made.

32:56.408 --> 32:59.711 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We are all foolproof and
incapable of error.

32:59.744 --> 33:06.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: The year 2001 came
and went without
any manned space odysseys of
note.

33:06.618 --> 33:08.353 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ACTOR: Open the pod bay doors,
Hal.

33:08.386 --> 33:12.023 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Much less ones with
the likes
of artificially intelligent Hal.

33:12.057 --> 33:14.226 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ACTOR: I'm sorry, Dave.

33:14.259 --> 33:16.294 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'm afraid I can't do that.

33:16.328 --> 33:22.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But most striking
to us is the
near-universal agreement about
the headwinds

33:22.701 --> 33:29.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
now facing U.S. economic growth:
problems
in education, an aging
population, a huge

33:29.341 --> 33:34.746 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
national debt, and, most of all,
growing inequality.

33:34.779 --> 33:39.451 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Economic historian Greg Clark
said he's long
been a techno-optimist.

33:39.484 --> 33:41.319 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But after reading Gordon's book:

33:41.353 --> 33:42.787 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
GREGORY CLARK, Economic
Historian, University
of California, Davis: I am
actually convinced

33:42.821 --> 33:46.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
now that the best of America is
behind us
in terms of economic growth.

33:46.558 --> 33:52.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Clark titled his
talk "Winter
Is Coming," a nod to the grim TV
series about

33:52.831 --> 33:56.301 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a more primitive time, HBO's
"Game of Thrones."

33:56.334 --> 34:01.806 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GREGORY CLARK: I titled it that
way because
I was struck, when I looked at
the future

34:01.840 --> 34:07.379 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the U.S. economy, how much it
was going
to resemble the medieval
economy.

34:07.412 --> 34:09.281 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: The medieval
economy?

34:09.314 --> 34:13.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GREGORY CLARK: The medieval
economy, in terms
of the types of jobs that people
now are doing,

34:13.518 --> 34:20.258 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
gardening, food preparing,
serving, cleaning,
bricklaying, carpentry.

34:20.292 --> 34:25.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You could get someone from 1400,
put them
on the job and in two hours,
they'd be perfectly

34:25.664 --> 34:26.831 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
functional.

34:26.865 --> 34:29.034 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Working, that is,
but hardly
getting by.

34:29.067 --> 34:35.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And to Robert Gordon, the
connection between
stagnant wages and today's
political unease

34:35.540 --> 34:37.175 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is obvious.

34:37.208 --> 34:40.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT GORDON: Because the heart
of slow wage
growth is slow productivity
growth.

34:40.879 --> 34:44.416 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And added to that is the
inequality that is
siphoning off the little
productivity that

34:44.449 --> 34:46.751 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we have got into the top 1
percent.

34:46.785 --> 34:50.689 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so the bottom 99 percent
have good reason
to be resentful and anxious.

34:50.722 --> 34:56.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: For the "PBS
NewsHour," this
is economics correspondent Paul
Solman, reporting

34:56.261 --> 34:59.597 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
from San Francisco.

34:59.631 --> 35:13.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Next: As we have
seen with recent
pandemics, emerging diseases
like Zika and

35:13.345 --> 35:18.183 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ebola can cross continents and
oceans with
uncontrolled speed.

35:18.216 --> 35:22.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Scientists are identifying areas
where new
infectious diseases are most
likely to emerge,

35:22.887 --> 35:27.025 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
where there are high risks of
animal viruses
passing to humans.

35:27.058 --> 35:29.894 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
One of those areas is Southern
China.

35:29.928 --> 35:34.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hari Sreenivasan brings us this
report, which
was produced in collaboration
with Global

35:34.232 --> 35:35.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Health Frontiers.

35:35.233 --> 35:37.002 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

35:37.035 --> 35:41.840 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PETER DASZAK, President,
EcoHealth Alliance:
We're in Guilin in Southern
China, in one

35:41.873 --> 35:46.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the most beautiful parts of
China with
these amazing limestone hills
and valleys

35:46.711 --> 35:49.414 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and very scenic and picturesque.

35:49.447 --> 35:54.853 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Peter Daszak
is the president
of EcoHealth Alliance, a
nonprofit organization

35:54.886 --> 35:59.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
based in New York dedicated to
protecting
wildlife and public health from
the emergence

35:59.758 --> 36:00.725 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of disease.

36:00.759 --> 36:02.660 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

36:02.694 --> 36:06.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER DASZAK: The reason we're
here is, we're
interested in the risk of new
diseases emerging

36:06.765 --> 36:12.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out of the wildlife trade in
China, just like
SARS did a few years ago and
just like ultimately

36:12.737 --> 36:16.674 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HIV did in Africa 40-odd years
ago.

36:16.708 --> 36:22.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If we can get to the source of
where they
come from and reduce the risk,
we could solve

36:22.947 --> 36:28.086 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a huge problem and save millions
of lives,
rather than waiting for them to
emerge and

36:28.119 --> 36:31.089 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
try to mop it up afterwards.

36:31.122 --> 36:37.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: At markets
across China,
like this one, people come in
daily to buy

36:37.262 --> 36:38.496 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
chickens and ducks.

36:38.530 --> 36:40.398 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

36:40.432 --> 36:43.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER DASZAK: It increases the
risk of a pathogen
like avian flu from spreading,
because you

36:43.601 --> 36:45.303 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
have got live chickens.

36:45.336 --> 36:50.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If one of them is infected, it
brings the
virus in, and it spreads to this
flock over

36:50.475 --> 36:56.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a few hours, and then those
animals are taken
to all distant parts of the
region.

36:56.514 --> 37:00.952 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, you could see this activity
anywhere
in the world.

37:00.985 --> 37:06.224 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is just like what happens
in rural America
and rural parts of Europe.

37:06.257 --> 37:10.161 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the difference is, here,
we're in a hot
zone for emerging diseases.

37:10.195 --> 37:15.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is a place where we have
repeatedly seen
outbreaks from poultry moving
into people

37:15.533 --> 37:17.368 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and spreading globally.

37:17.402 --> 37:22.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Natural
habitats can also
contribute to the spread of
viruses.

37:22.107 --> 37:23.241 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

37:23.274 --> 37:25.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PETER DASZAK: We have got people
fishing in
the river.

37:25.110 --> 37:27.445 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have got people washing in
the river.

37:27.479 --> 37:30.715 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We know there is sewage coming
directly from
